{"title_page": "Releasing the Demons", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name     = Releasing the Demons\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[Godsmack]]\n| album    = [[Faceless]]\n| released = {{Start date|2003|04|8}}\n| format   = [[CD]]\n| recorded = 2002\n| studio   = The Hit Factory Criteria\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Nu metal]]\n| length   = {{Duration|m=4|s=12}}\n| label    = [[Republic Records|Republic/Universal]]\n| writer   = [[Sully Erna]]\n| producer = [[David Bottrill]], [[Sully Erna]]\n}}\n\n'''\"Releasing the Demons\"''' is a song by the [[rock music|rock]] band [[Godsmack]] from their third studio album ''[[Faceless]]'' and was written by frontman [[Sully Erna]].\n\n==Song meaning==\n\nGodsmack lead singer Sully Erna is a [[Wicca]]n,<ref>{{cite web|title=Sully Erna of Godsmack on Karma, Christians, and the Law of Three|url=http://www.nyrock.com/interviews/1999/godsmack_int.asp|website=NYRock Magazine|accessdate=March 3, 2015|date=October 1999|quote=NYROCK: You make no secret of the fact that you practice Wicca [Neo-Pagan religion with many traditions that pre-date Christianity].}}</ref> and in the Wiccan religion, there is a [[Rule of Three (Wicca)|threefold rule]]: Whatever you send out, whether it be good or bad, comes back to you three times. In this song, Sully had released demons from his body resulting in more demons returning. In the middle of the song, Sully speaks with laughter of the demons coming back to him threefold.\n\n==Other uses==\n\nThe riff of this song is frequently used by conservative radio talk show host [[Michael Smerconish]] as [[bumper music]] at the end of on-air segments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yago-knowledge.org/resource/Releasing_the_Demons|title=Godsmack's Song Is Using In Talk Show|publisher=Yago Knowledge.org|date=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n\n* [[Sully Erna]] \u2013 rhythm guitar, lead vocals\n* [[Tony Rombola]] \u2013 lead guitar\n* [[Robbie Merrill]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Shannon Larkin]] \u2013 drums\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|godsmack|releasing-the-demons}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Godsmack}}\n\n[[Category:Godsmack songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sully Erna]]\n[[Category:2003 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Bottrill]]\n[[Category:Neopagan songs]]\n[[Category:Wicca in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name     = Releasing the Demons\n| cover    =\n| alt      =\n| type     =\n| artist   = [[Godsmack]]\n| album    = [[Faceless]]\n| released = {{Start date|2003|04|8}}\n| format   = [[CD]]\n| recorded = 2002\n| studio   = The Hit Factory Criteria\n| venue    =\n| genre    = [[Nu metal]]\n| length   = {{Duration|m=4|s=12}}\n| label    = [[Republic Records|Republic/Universal]]\n| writer   = [[Sully Erna]]\n| producer = [[David Bottrill]], [[Sully Erna]]\n}}\n\n'''\"Releasing the Demons\"''' is a song by the [[rock music|rock]] band [[Godsmack]] from their third studio album ''[[Faceless]]'' and was written by frontman [[Sully Erna]].\n\n==Song meaning==\n\nGodsmack lead singer Sully Erna is a Wiccan,<ref>{{cite web|title=Sully Erna of Godsmack on Karma, Christians, and the Law of Three|url=http://www.nyrock.com/interviews/1999/godsmack_int.asp|website=NYRock Magazine|accessdate=March 3, 2015|date=October 1999|quote=NYROCK: You make no secret of the fact that you practice Wicca [Neo-Pagan religion with many traditions that pre-date Christianity].}}</ref> and in the Wiccan religion, there is a [[Rule of Three (Wicca)|threefold rule]]: Whatever you send out, whether it be good or bad, comes back to you three times. In this song, Sully had released demons from his body resulting in more demons returning. In the middle of the song, Sully speaks with laughter of the demons coming back to him threefold.\n\n==Other uses==\n\nThe riff of this song is frequently used by conservative radio talk show host [[Michael Smerconish]] as [[bumper music]] at the end of on-air segments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yago-knowledge.org/resource/Releasing_the_Demons|title=Godsmack's Song Is Using In Talk Show|publisher=Yago Knowledge.org|date=August 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n\n* [[Sully Erna]] \u2013 rhythm guitar, lead vocals\n* [[Tony Rombola]] \u2013 lead guitar\n* [[Robbie Merrill]] \u2013 bass\n* [[Shannon Larkin]] \u2013 drums\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|godsmack|releasing-the-demons}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Godsmack}}\n\n[[Category:Godsmack songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Sully Erna]]\n[[Category:2003 songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Bottrill]]\n[[Category:Neopagan songs]]\n[[Category:Wicca in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Ffranc", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Releasing_the_Demons"}
{"title_page": "1986\u201387 Divizia B", "text_new": "{{Infobox football league season\n | country                    = {{ROU}}\n | competition                = [[Liga II|Divizia B]]\n | season                     = 1986\u201387\n | teams                      = 54 (3x18)\n | promoted                   = [[CSM Suceava]]<br />[[ASA 1962 T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219|ASA T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219]]<br />[[FC Politehnica Timi\u0219oara|Politehnica Timi\u0219oara]]\n | relegated                  = [[CS Aerostar Bac\u0103u|Aripile Victoria Bac\u0103u]]<br />[[ROVA Ro\u0219iori]]<br />[[CSA Aurul Brad|Aurul Brad]]<br />[[Minerul Gura Humorului]]<br />[[Carpa\u021bi M\u00e2r\u0219a]]<br />[[Mure\u0219ul Deva (1921)|Mure\u0219ul Deva]]<br />[[FCM Dun\u0103rea Gala\u021bi|Dun\u0103rea CSU Gala\u021bi]]<br />[[Automatica Bucure\u0219ti]]<br />[[CFR Cluj|Steaua CFR Cluj]]<br />[[FCM C\u00e2mpina|Poiana C\u00e2mpina]]<br />[[Oltul Sf\u00e2ntu Gheorghe|IMASA Sf\u00e2ntu Gheorghe]]<br />[[AS Minerul Cavnic|Minerul Cavnic]]\n | league topscorer           =\n | biggest home win           =\n | biggest away win           =\n | highest scoring            =\n | matches                    =\n | total goals                =\n | longest wins               =\n | longest unbeaten           =\n | longest losses             =\n | highest attendance         =\n | lowest attendance          =\n | average attendance         =\n | prevseason                 = [[1985\u201386 Divizia B|1985\u201386]]\n | nextseason                 = [[1987\u201388 Divizia B|1987\u201388]]\n}}\n\nThe '''1986\u201387 [[Divizia B]]''' was the 47th season of the second tier of the [[Romanian football league system]].\n\nThe format has been maintained to three series, each of them having 18 teams. At the end of the season the winners of the series promoted to [[Liga I|Divizia A]] and the last four places from each series relegated to [[Liga III|Divizia C]].<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/tablesr/roem2hist.html#87 rsssf.com]</ref><ref>[http://www.romaniansoccer.ro/divizia_b/tables/1986_87.shtml romaniansoccer.ro]</ref>\n\n== Team changes ==\n{{col-begin|width=auto}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===To Divizia B===\n'''Promoted from [[1985\u201386 Divizia C|Divizia C]]'''\n* [[Minerul Gura Humorului]]\n* [[CSM Foc\u0219ani|Unirea Dinamo Foc\u0219ani]]\n* [[FEPA 74 B\u00e2rlad]]\n* [[AFC Unirea Slobozia|Unirea Slobozia]]\n* [[AFC Rocar Bucure\u0219ti|Autobuzul Bucure\u0219ti]]\n* [[ROVA Ro\u0219iori]]\n* [[CS Pandurii T\u00e2rgu Jiu|Gloria Pandurii]]\n* [[Minerul Paro\u0219eni]]\n* [[CFR Cluj|Steaua CFR Cluj]]\n* [[Unio Satu Mare]]\n* [[FC Inter Sibiu|Inter Sibiu]]\n* [[FCM C\u00e2mpina|Poiana C\u00e2mpina]]\n\n'''Relegated from [[1985\u201386 Divizia A|Divizia A]]'''\n* [[FC Politehnica Timi\u0219oara|Politehnica Timi\u0219oara]]\n* [[ASA 1962 T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219|ASA T\u00e2rgu Mure\u0219]]\n* [[FC Bihor Oradea|Bihor Oradea]]\n{{col-break|gap=5em}}\n\n===From Divizia B===\n'''Relegated to [[1986\u201387 Divizia C|Divizia C]]'''\n* [[Metalul Plopeni]]\n* [[Muscelul C\u00e2mpulung]]\n* [[FC CFR Timi\u0219oara|CFR Timi\u0219oara]]\n* [[FC Dun\u0103rea C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i|Dun\u0103rea C\u0103l\u0103ra\u0219i]]\n* [[CSM Av\u00e2ntul Reghin|Av\u00e2ntul Reghin]]\n* [[FC Unirea Alba Iulia|Unirea Alba Iulia]]\n* [[Foresta F\u0103lticeni|Chimia F\u0103lticeni]]\n* [[\u0218oimii Sibiu|\u0218oimii IPA Sibiu]]\n* [[\u00cenfr\u0103\u021birea Oradea]]\n* [[Minerul Vatra Dornei]]\n* [[ICSIM Bucure\u0219ti]]\n* [[CS Minerul Lupeni|Minerul Lupeni]]\n\n'''Promoted to [[1986\u201387 Divizia A|Divizia A]]'''\n* [[ASC O\u021belul Gala\u021bi|O\u021belul Gala\u021bi]]\n* [[CSM Flac\u0103ra Moreni|Flac\u0103ra Moreni]]\n* [[CSM Jiul Petro\u0219ani|Jiul Petro\u0219ani]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n===Renamed teams===\n''Aripile Bac\u0103u'' was renamed as [[CS Aerostar Bac\u0103u|Aripile Victoria Bac\u0103u]].\n\n''Delta Tulcea'' was renamed as [[FC Delta Dobrogea Tulcea|Delta Dinamo Tulcea]].\n\n==League tables==\n===Serie I===\n{{#invoke:Spor