con|Guyana}} '''[[Nigel Codrington]]''' ||'''11'''\n|- bgcolor=#D0E7FF\n|'''2.'''\n|{{flagicon|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}} [[Shandel Samuel]] ||10\n|- bgcolor=#F5FAFF\n|'''3.'''\n|{{flagicon|CUB}} [[Reinier Alc\u00e1ntara]] ||7\n|- bgcolor=#D0E7FF\n|'''4.'''\n|{{flagicon|Barbados}} [[Paul Ifill]] ||6\n|- bgcolor=#F5FAFF\n|\n|{{flagicon|GLP|local}} [[Dominique Mocka]] ||6\n|- bgcolor=#D0E7FF\n|\n|{{flagicon|TRI}} [[Gary Glasgow]] ||6\n|- bgcolor=#F5FAFF\n|'''7.'''\n|{{flagicon|Guyana}} [[Gregory Richardson]] ||5\n|- bgcolor=#D0E7FF\n|\n|{{flagicon|Dominican Republic}} [[Jonathan Fa\u00f1a]] ||5\n|- bgcolor=#F5FAFF\n|\n|{{flagicon|Guyana}} [[Randolph Jerome]] ||5\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061005231504/http://www.digicelfootball.com/en/ Digicel Caribbean Cup 2007 Official Site]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061105061505/http://www.concacaf.com/competitions/goldcup/ Caribbean Cup 2007 on CONCACAF Website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090524172642/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesc/caribe07.html Digicel Cup 2007 at RSSSF]\n\n{{Caribbean Cup}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2007}}\n[[Category:Caribbean Cup]]\n[[Category:2007 in Trinidad and Tobago football|Carib]]\n[[Category:International association football competitions hosted by Trinidad and Tobago]]\n[[Category:2006\u201307 in Caribbean football]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox international football competition\n| tourney_name =\n| year = 2006\u201307\n| other_titles    = Digicel Caribbean Cup 2007\n| image =\n| size =\n| caption =\n| country = Trinidad and Tobago\n| country2 =\n| dates = 2 September 2006 \u2013 9 January 2007 (qualifiers)<br />12 January 2007 \u2013 23 January 2007 (finals)\n| num_teams = 25\n| confederations = 1\n| finalists = 8\n| venues = 12\n| cities = 10\n| champion = Haiti\n| count = 1\n| second = Trinidad and Tobago\n| third =  Cuba\n| fourth = Guadeloupe\n| fourth-flagvar  = local\n| matches = 72\n| goals = 251\n| attendance =\n| top_scorer = {{flagicon|Guyana}} [[Nigel Codrington]] (11 goals)\n| player =\n| updated =\n| prevseason = [[2005 Caribbean Cup|2005]]\n| nextseason = [[2008 Caribbean Cup|2008]]\n}}\nThe '''2007 Caribbean Cup''' (known as the '''[[Digicel]] Caribbean Cup''' for sponsorship reasons) is the fourteenth edition of the biennial [[Caribbean Cup]], the finals of which were contested in [[Trinidad and Tobago]] between 12 January and 23 January 2007. The four semifinalists ([[Cuba national football team|Cuba]], [[Guadeloupe national football team|Guadeloupe]], [[Haiti national football team|Haiti]], and hosts [[Trinidad and Tobago national football team|Trinidad and Tobago]]) qualified for the [[2007 CONCACAF Gold Cup|2007]] edition of the [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]]. In all, 24 of the eligible countries participated (5 did not enter and 1 withdrew).\n\n[[Haiti national football team|Haiti]] eventually won the tournament despite having to qualify for the finals through a play-off of third-place teams from the second round and finishing second in its final-round group. Haiti beat eight-time champion and host Trinidad and Tobago in the final, although Trinidad and Tobago was missing overseas players that had helped them qualify for the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]]. [[Guadeloupe national football team|Guadeloupe]] were the surprise of the tournament, as former French international [[Jocelyn Angloma]] came out of retirement to help the team advance to the semifinals, qualifying for its first Gold Cup in the process. [[Cuba national football team|Cuba]] continued its development in the region by finishing in third place.\n\n==Prize money==\n* {{fb|HAI}}, as the '''winner''', received US$120,000 (UK \u00a364,022).\n* {{fb|TRI}}, as the '''runner up''', received US$70,000 (UK \u00a337,350).\n* {{fb|CUB}}, as the '''third-place team''', received US$50,000 (UK \u00a326,680).\n* {{fb|GLP|local}}, as the '''fourth-place team''', received US$30,000 (UK \u00a316,009).\n* Each of the ten host countries received a subsistence package of US$20,000 (UK \u00a310,673).  Additionally, the '''host''' of the '''Digicel Caribbean Cup Final''' received US$150,000 (UK \u00a380,047) to compensate for the increased costs of holding the final round of the competition.\n\n(UK \u00a3 values calculated on 28 September 2006)\n\n==First Qualifying Round==\n{{fb|TRI}} receive bye to final round. {{fb|ARU}}, {{fb|GYF|local}}, {{fb|MSR}}, {{fb|PUR}} and {{fb|Sint Maarten}} did not enter.\n\n===Summary===\nThe first round produced some notable upsets. Guyana surprised many by dominating Group A, and Surinam qualified for the second round as well. Group host Netherlands Antilles finished last by capturing a lone draw. Group B did not go to form, either; though Barbados fulfilled widely held expectations by winning, host Antigua & Barbuda produced a minor shock by also making it out of the group at the expense of St. Kitts & Nevis. St. Kitts had a late penalty kick to be taken by [[Atiba Harris]] that if made would have eliminated Antigua & Barbuda in the group's final game, but the Antiguan goalkeeper saved the penalty. Group C went to form, save only that the British Virgin Islands withdrew before group play started. Bermuda expectedly dominated the group. The shocker of the round, though occurred in Group D, where host Jamaica, widely considered the best national footballing side in the Caribbean, did not advance to the second round. Jamaica lost their second game to St. Vincent & Grenadines 2\u20131. Playing in the final game on the group's last day knowing they had to defeat Haiti by 3 goals to qualify, Jamaica could only muster a 2\u20130 victory, meaning that St. Vincent & Grenadines pulled the upset and advanced to the second round based on goals scored. Despite their loss to Jamaica, Haiti won the group based on goal differential. Host Cuba won Group E, with the Bahamas advancing as well by defeating a surprisingly competitive Turks & Caicos team. In Group F, the French departments of Martinique and host Guadeloupe carried on easily, with the host winning the group.\n\n===Group A===\nPlayed in [[Netherlands Antilles]] at [[Stadion Ergilio Hato]].\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=165|Team\n!width=20|Pld\n!width=20|W\n!width=20|D\n!width=20|L\n!width=20|GF\n!width=20|GA\n!width=20|GD\n!width=20|Pts\n|- align=center style=\"background:#ccffcc;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|GUY}}\n|3||3||0||0||11||0||+11||'''9'''\n|- align=center style=\"background:#ccffcc;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|SUR}}\n|3||2||0||1||2||5||\u22123||'''6'''\n|- align=center style=\"background:#f5f5f5;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|GRN}}\n|3||0||1||2||1||3||\u22122||'''1'''\n|- align=center style=\"background:#f5f5f5;\"\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{fb|ANT}}\n|3||0||1||2||1||7||\u22126||'''1'''\n|}\n\n{{footballbox|date = 6 September 2006|team1 = {{fb-rt|SUR}}|score = 0\u20135|report= |team2 = {{fb|GUY}}|goals1 = |goals2 =[[Gregory Richardson|Richardson]] {{goal|4}}<br />[[Nigel Codrington|Codrington]] {{goal|15||73}}<br /> [[Randolph Jerome|Jerome]] {{goal|42}}<br />[[Anthony Abrams|Abrams]] {{goal|90}}|stadium = [[Stadion Ergilio Hato]], [[Willemstad]] | referee = Rudolph Angela ([[Aruba]])\n}}\n{{footballbox|date = 6 September 2006|team1 = {{fb-rt|ANT}}|score = 1\u20131|report= |team2 = {{fb|GRN}}|goals1 = [[Tyrone Maria|Maria]] {{goal|1}}|goals2 =[[Dennis Rennie|Rennie]] {{goal|52}}|stadium = [[Stadion Ergilio Hato]], [[Willemstad]] | referee = Willy Minyetty<br />([[Dominican Republic]])\n}}\n----\n{{footballbox|date = 8 September 2006|team1 = {{fb-rt|SUR}}|score = 1\u20130|report= |team2 = {{fb|GRN}}|goals1 = [[Gorden Kinsaine|Kinsaine]] {{goal|35}}|goals2 = |stadium = [[Stadion Ergilio Hato]], [[Willemstad]] | referee = Lee Davis<br> ([[Trinidad & Tobago]])\n}}\n{{footballbox|date = 8 September 2006|team1 = {{fb-rt|ANT}}|score = 0\u20135|report= |team2 = {{fb|GUY}}|goals1 = |goals2 =